GEM ENCYCLOPEDIA OF MEDICINE

X-Ray Imaging Technologies

Soft Tissue Structures
The various soft tissues within the body, which can be distinguished using ultrasound.

Computer
A device that translates data from the ultrasound receiver into an image on a television screen.

Television Screen
A display screen that shows the image generated by the computer from the ultrasound data.

Sonar Technology
Technology developed during World War II to detect submarines, which led to the development of medical ultrasound.

Bile Ducts
Tubes that carry digestive enzymes from the gallbladder and liver to the intestines.

Gallbladder
An organ in the body, usually found in the gallbladder, pancreas and kidneys, where calculi can form.<SEP>An organ that can suffer from painful inflammation due to calculi and obstruct bile ducts.<SEP>An organ that stores bile and can be affected by gallstones.<SEP>The gallbladder is an organ that may be examined using ultrasound, requiring specific patient preparation.

Part of the digestive system that receives digestive enzymes.<SEP>The destination of digestive enzymes carried from the gallbladder and liver.<SEP>The intestines are organs that are difficult to image with ultrasound due to the presence of gas.<SEP>The intestines receive bile from the liver and gallbladder through the common bile duct, as well as digestive enzymes from the pancreas.<SEP>The location from which bacteria or amoeba can spread to the liver, causing liver abscesses.<SEP>The origin point of bacteria or amoeba that can cause liver abscesses.

Emergency Room
A department in a hospital that provides immediate medical care for emergency situations.

Ambulance Service
A service that provides emergency medical transportation and care.

Tumors
Abnormal growths that can be located and identified with ultrasound.

Cysts
Cysts are closed sacs that can form as part of severe acne.<SEP>Fluid-filled sacs that can be located and distinguished from solid tumors with ultrasound.

Abscesses
Collections of pus that can be located and identified with ultrasound.

Scar Tissue
Fibrous tissue that forms after an injury and can be located with ultrasound.

Accessory Organs
Additional organs or structures that can be located with ultrasound.

Liver
An organ that works with the gallbladder to carry digestive enzymes to the intestines.<SEP>An organ where abscesses can be found.<SEP>An organ where abscesses can form due to bacterial or amoebic infection.<SEP>The liver is an organ that can be harmed by acetaminophen, especially when combined with alcohol.<SEP>The liver produces bile, which travels to the intestines through the common bile duct. Cirrhosis affects the liver.<SEP>The organ where GH causes the production of IGF-1.

Spleen
An organ near the adrenal glands that requires careful attention during surgery.<SEP>An organ prone to injury during abdominal trauma and can become painfully inflamed due to infection or cancer.<SEP>An organ where abscesses can be found.<SEP>The location where monocytes are formed.<SEP>The spleen is an organ that filters out antibody-marked platelets in individuals with autoimmune disorders like ITP.

Kidneys
An organ in the body, usually found in the gallbladder, pancreas and kidneys, where calculi can form.<SEP>Organs near which the adrenal glands are located.<SEP>Organs prone to traumatic injury and calculi formation, which can block urine flow and cause blood poisoning.<SEP>Organs that can be injured due to lack of sufficient oxygen in ARDS patients.<SEP>The kidneys are organs located near the adrenal glands.

Doctor
A doctor diagnoses kidney failure and may consult with a nephrologist.<SEP>A doctor is a medical professional who conducts ultrasound procedures with the assistance of a technologist.<SEP>A medical professional who can perform ultrasound procedures, but whose credentials should be verified.<SEP>A medical professional who performs abortions and provides aftercare.<SEP>A medical professional who provides care and treatment to patients, including administering medications and monitoring the abortion process.

Technicians
Medical personnel who operate ultrasound equipment, and whose credentials should be verified.

Obese People
A category of patients who may not be good candidates for abdominal ultrasound due to body type.

Digestive Malady
A general term for illnesses affecting the digestive system.

Calculi
Hard concretions or stones that can cause inflammation and obstruction in organs like the gallbladder and kidneys.<SEP>Stones formed by the accumulation of excess mineral salts and other organic material such as blood or mucous, usually found in the gallbladder, pancreas, and kidneys.

Ultrasound Waves
Sound waves used in medical imaging, with frequencies between 1 and 10 MHz.

Medical Condition
A general term for any health issue or disease.

Pregnant Woman
A woman who is expecting a child and should consult her doctor before undergoing an abdominal ultrasound.

Medical Tool
A device or method used in medical diagnosis or treatment.

Doctors and technicians who operate ultrasound equipment and interpret the results.

Kidney Morphology
The structure and form of the kidneys.

Lower Body
The part of the body below the abdomen.

Tumor Cells
Cells from a tumor that are extracted for biopsy.

Biopsy
The process of extracting tissue for diagnostic purposes.

Ultrasonic Waves
Sound waves with frequencies above the range of human hearing, used for therapeutic purposes.

Surgical Procedure
A medical procedure involving incision or manipulation of tissues.

Pancreas
An organ in the body, usually found in the gallbladder, pancreas and kidneys, where calculi can form. It also produces digestive enzymes that enter the intestines through the common bile duct.<SEP>An organ near the adrenal glands that requires careful attention during surgery.<SEP>An organ that, in rare cases, can produce GHRH, leading to increased GH production.<SEP>The pancreas is an organ where certain tumors can produce GHRH.

Common Bile Duct
The branching passage through which bile travels from the liver and gallbladder into the small intestine. Digestive enzymes from the pancreas also enter the intestines through the common bile duct. Obstruction can cause jaundice.

Abdomen
A location where actinomycosis can occur.<SEP>The abdomen is the part of the body that is scanned using ultrasound technology.<SEP>The abdomen is the region of the body being scanned by ultrasound.<SEP>The location of the psoas muscles, where abscesses can develop.<SEP>The part of the body where abdominal ultrasound imaging is performed.

B-Mode Scanning
A type of ultrasound scanning combined with Doppler capability to produce images of blood vessels from which blood flow can be directly measured.

Doppler Ultrasonography
A type of ultrasonography that includes the capability of accurately measuring velocities of moving material, such as blood in arteries and veins.

Jaundice
A condition that results in a yellow tint to the skin, eyes, and body fluids, often associated with liver or gallbladder issues.

Cirrhosis
A chronic liver disease characterized by the invasion of connective tissue and the degeneration of proper functioning.

Vibrations Per Second
The unit of measurement for frequency, which corresponds to pitch in audible sounds.

Frequency
The rate at which a vibration occurs, measured in vibrations per second. In the audible range, it determines pitch.

Pitch
The perceived highness or lowness of a sound, determined by its frequency.

Mineral Salts
Components that, along with other organic material, accumulate to form calculi.

Organic Material
Substances such as blood or mucous that, along with mineral salts, accumulate to form calculi.

Blood

Mucous

Fluids
Fluids are administered intravenously to patients with kidney failure to treat their primary condition.<SEP>Substances, such as bile or urine, whose proper flow can be obstructed by calculi.

Bile
A fluid produced by the liver that aids in digestion and can be obstructed by calculi.

Urine
A fluid produced by the kidneys that can be obstructed by calculi.<SEP>Bodily fluid tested for blood and protein in the diagnosis of APSGN.<SEP>Urine is a bodily fluid that can be foamy or bloody in cases of kidney problems, indicating protein or blood presence.

Bladder
The organ that stores urine, which can be affected by calculi.

Ionizing Radiation
Radiation that can damage living tissue by disrupting and destroying individual cells at the molecular level.

Living Tissue
Biological material that can be damaged by ionizing radiation.

Nuclear Radiation
Types of radiation, including x-rays, gamma rays, and beta rays, that are potentially ionizing.

X-Rays
A type of nuclear radiation that is potentially ionizing.<SEP>X-rays are a diagnostic imaging technique used to determine the cause of kidney failure and assess the level of remaining kidney function.

Ultrasound
Ultrasound is a medical imaging technique that uses sound waves to create images of internal body structures.

Technologist
A technologist is a skilled professional who operates the ultrasound equipment during the procedure.

Ovaries
Female sex glands that produce hormones, including estrogens, which can influence acne development.<SEP>The ovaries are organs that may be examined using ultrasound, requiring specific patient preparation.

Veins
Veins are blood vessels that may be examined using ultrasound, requiring specific patient preparation.

Kidney Stones

Cirrhosis of the liver is a condition that can be diagnosed using ultrasound.

Intestinal folds are anatomical structures within the intestines that can be obscured during ultrasound imaging.

Gas
Gas within the body, particularly in the intestines, can disrupt ultrasound images.

Body
The human body, specifically the abdomen, is the subject of the ultrasound imaging procedure.

Echo
An echo is a reflection of ultrasound waves from tissues and organs, used to create an image.

Tissue
Tissue is a type of biological material that reflects ultrasound waves differently, affecting image brightness.

Organ
An organ is a body part that can be imaged using ultrasound.

Patient
A patient is an individual undergoing an abdominal ultrasound procedure.

Gel
A special gel is used to facilitate the transmission of ultrasound waves between the probe and the skin.

Skin
The outer layer of the body, where abscesses can form.<SEP>The skin is the outer layer of the body that the ultrasound probe contacts.

Ultrasound Probe
The ultrasound probe is a device used to transmit and receive ultrasonic pulses.

Stomach
An organ where abscesses can be found.<SEP>One of the twelve main organs in Chinese medicine, associated with specific chi energy.<SEP>Part of the woman's body where a needle is inserted during an abortion procedure.<SEP>The stomach is an organ that is difficult to image with ultrasound due to the presence of gas.<SEP>The stomach is an organ that receives food from the esophagus and processes it before passing it to the intestines.<SEP>The stomach is the organ that receives food from the esophagus.

The bowel is an organ that is difficult to image with ultrasound due to the presence of gas.

A-Mode
A-mode is a type of ultrasound used to measure distances within the body.

Selective Serotonin Reuptake Inhibitors
A class of antidepressant medications used to treat anxiety disorders.

Fluoxetine (Prozac)
A selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor (SSRI) used to treat anxiety disorders.

Sertraline (Zoloft)
A selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor (SSRI) used to treat anxiety disorders.

Alprazolam (Xanax)
A benzodiazepine tranquilizer used to manage panic attacks.

Clonazepam (Klonipin)
A benzodiazepine tranquilizer used to manage panic attacks.

Phobias
A type of anxiety disorder characterized by persistent and excessive fear of an object or situation.

Cognitive Behavioral Therapy
A type of psychotherapy that helps patients change negative thinking patterns and behaviors.

Psychodynamically Oriented Psychotherapy
A type of psychotherapy that explores unconscious emotional conflicts.

Pantheon Books
A book publisher that published the book 'Worry: Controlling It and Using It Wisely.'

AZT
AZT is an anti-retroviral medication used in combination with other medications for treating HIV.

Europe
A continent where HIV-1 causes most cases of AIDS.<SEP>Europe is a continent where most cases of sexually transmitted HIV infection have resulted from homosexual contact.<SEP>Europe is a region where HIV-1 causes most cases of AIDS.

Men
Men are mentioned in the context of bisexual men who may transmit HIV to their wives and in comparison to women regarding AIDS diagnosis and survival rates.<SEP>Refers to the male population, specifically in the context of hematocrit levels.

CD4
A type of protein molecule in human blood present on the surface of T cells, serving as a receptor for the HIV virus. Its depletion indicates immune system damage.<SEP>CD4 is a protein found on the surface of helper T cells, which HIV binds to, leading to immunodeficiency.

CCR5
CCR5 is a chemokine receptor that helps mediate the entry of HIV into cells. Defects in its structure can slow or prevent the progression of AIDS.

Persistent Generalized Lymphadenopathy (PGL)
Persistent Generalized Lymphadenopathy (PGL) is a condition in which HIV continues to produce chronic painless swellings in the lymph nodes during the latency period.

Injured Worker
An injured worker who is receiving AZT as part of their treatment.

Safe Sex
Practicing safe sex is a preventative measure against HIV transmission.

Monogamous
Being monogamous is a lifestyle choice that reduces the risk of HIV transmission.

Anal Intercourse
Anal intercourse is a sexual activity associated with a higher risk of HIV transmission.

data.entity_name: Partner With Symptoms Of Advanced HIV Infection
data.content:
Partner With Symptoms Of Advanced HIV Infection
A person exhibiting symptoms of advanced HIV infection who can transmit the virus to others.

Sexually Transmitted Diseases (STDs)
Sexually transmitted diseases (STDs) are infections that can increase the risk of HIV transmission.

Homosexual Contact
Homosexual contact is a mode of HIV transmission, particularly in the United States and Europe.

Heterosexuals
Heterosexuals are a group among whom AIDS is primarily spread through sexual intercourse in Africa.

High-Risk Mothers
High-risk mothers are women who are at increased risk of transmitting HIV to their children.

Bisexual Men
Bisexual men are a risk group for transmitting HIV to their female partners.

data.entity_name: Men Who Have An Abnormal Blood Condition Called Hemophilia
data.content:
Men Who Have An Abnormal Blood Condition Called Hemophilia
Men with hemophilia requiring blood transfusions are at risk of HIV infection.

Intravenous Drug Users
Intravenous drug users are a high-risk group for HIV infection due to needle sharing.<SEP>Intravenous drug users are at high risk of HIV infection due to shared needles.

data.entity_name: Neighborhoods With A High Rate Of HIV
data.content:
Neighborhoods With A High Rate Of HIV
Neighborhoods with a high rate of HIV are areas where women are at higher risk of HIV infection.

Hadenopathy (PGL)
Hadenopathy, also known as Persistent Generalized Lymphadenopathy (PGL), is a condition characterized by chronic painless swellings in the lymph nodes during the latency period of HIV infection.

Autoimmunity
Autoimmunity is a condition where the body's immune system produces antibodies that attack its own cells, such as blood platelets, leading to disorders like immune-related thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP).

Acute Retroviral Syndrome
Acute retroviral syndrome is a group of symptoms resembling mononucleosis that are often the first sign of HIV infection.<SEP>Acute retroviral syndrome is an early stage of HIV infection characterized by symptoms resembling mononucleosis, such as fever, fatigue, muscle aches, and swollen lymph nodes.

Meningitis
Meningitis is an inflammation of the membranes covering the brain and spinal cord, which can occur during the acute retroviral syndrome phase of HIV infection.

Opportunistic Infections
Infections that take advantage of a weakened immune system, common in AIDS patients.<SEP>Opportunistic infections are infections caused by organisms that take advantage of a weakened immune system, common in AIDS patients. Examples include fungal infections like Pneumocystis carinii pneumonia (PCP) and yeast infections, protozoal infections like toxoplasmosis, and mycobacterial infections like tuberculosis or MAC infections.

PCP)
Pneumocystis carinii pneumonia (PCP) is a common and often fatal fungal infection associated with AIDS, serving as an important measure of a patient's prognosis.

Toxoplasmosis
Toxoplasmosis is a common opportunistic infection in AIDS patients caused by a protozoan.

MAC Infections
MAC infections are caused by Mycobacterium avium-intracellulare and occur in about 40% of AIDS patients.<SEP>Mycobacterium avium-intracellulare (MAC) infections are bacterial infections that occur in about 40% of AIDS patients.

CD4+ Lymphocytes
CD4+ lymphocytes are a subset of T lymphocytes that are crucial for immune system regulation and are monitored in AIDS patients.<SEP>CD4+ lymphocytes are a subset of T lymphocytes that are targeted and destroyed by the HIV virus, leading to immune system damage in AIDS patients.<SEP>CD4+ lymphocytes are immune cells that are monitored to assess the progression of HIV and the effectiveness of medications. A low count indicates progression to AIDS.

Nonprogressors
Nonprogressors are individuals infected with HIV who never progress to the late stage of the disease (AIDS).

Immune-Related Thrombocytopenic Purpura (ITP)
Immune-related thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP) is a disorder in which the number of blood platelets drops to abnormally low levels in some AIDS patients.

Mononucleosis
Mononucleosis is a viral infection whose symptoms resemble those of acute retroviral syndrome, an early sign of HIV infection.

Fungi
Fungi are a class of organisms that can cause opportunistic infections in AIDS patients, such as PCP and candidiasis.

Protozoa
Protozoa are a class of organisms that can cause opportunistic infections in AIDS patients, such as toxoplasmosis.

Mycobacteria
Mycobacteria are a class of bacteria that can cause opportunistic infections in AIDS patients, such as tuberculosis and MAC infections.

Mycobacterium Avium-Intracellulare
Mycobacterium avium-intracellulare is the bacteria that causes MAC infections.

CD4+
CD4+ cells are immune cells, and their count falling below 50 cells/mm3 is associated with the occurrence of AIDS dementia complex.

AIDS Dementia Complex
AIDS dementia complex is a neurological complication of AIDS, marked by loss of reasoning ability, memory loss, and other cognitive and motor impairments.

Cytomegalovirus (CMV)
Cytomegalovirus is a virus to which AIDS patients are highly vulnerable.

Herpes Simplex Virus (HSV)
Herpes simplex virus is a virus to which AIDS patients are highly vulnerable.

Varicella Zoster Virus (VZV)
Varicella zoster virus is a virus to which AIDS patients are highly vulnerable.

Epstein-Barr Virus (EBV)
Epstein-Barr virus is a virus to which AIDS patients are highly vulnerable and causes hairy leukoplakia.

JC Virus
JC virus causes progressive destruction of brain tissue in AIDS patients, leading to multifocal leukoencephalopathy (PML).

data.entity_name: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
data.content:
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) is a US government agency that regards multifocal leukoencephalopathy (PML) as an AIDS-defining illness and hairy leukoplakia as an indicator of AIDS.

Musculoskeletal Complications
Musculoskeletal complications are inflammations of the muscles, particularly in the hip area, and arthritis-like pains in the joints that may develop in late-stage AIDS patients.

Oral Symptoms
Oral symptoms in AIDS patients include thrush, painful ulcers in the mouth, and hairy leukoplakia of the tongue.

Hairy Leukoplakia of the Tongue
Hairy leukoplakia of the tongue is a white area of diseased tissue on the tongue, caused by the Epstein-Barr virus, and is an indicator of AIDS.

Hemophilia
Hemophilia is a hereditary blood coagulation disorder where blood does not clot properly, potentially requiring blood transfusions.

Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV)
Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) is a transmissible retrovirus that causes AIDS in humans. Two forms are HIV-1 and HIV-2.

North and South America
North and South America are regions where HIV-1 causes most cases of AIDS.

West Africa
A region where HIV-2 is chiefly found in patients.<SEP>West Africa is a region where HIV-2 is chiefly found in patients.

HIV Virus
The HIV virus infects cells with CD4 surface proteins, leading to the depletion of T cells, B cells, natural killer cells, and monocytes in the patient’s blood.

T Cells
Cells in the human immune system that are stimulated by interleukin-2 to respond to infections.<SEP>T cells are lymphocytes that originate in the thymus gland and regulate the immune system's response to infections, including HIV. CD4 lymphocytes are a subset of T lymphocytes.

B Cells
A type of white blood cell derived from bone marrow that secretes antibodies and has complex functions within the human immune system.<SEP>B cells are a type of immune cell that is depleted in AIDS patients due to HIV infection.<SEP>Cells in the human immune system that are stimulated by interleukin-2 to respond to infections.

Natural Killer Cells
Natural killer cells are a type of immune cell that is depleted in AIDS patients due to HIV infection.

Monocytes
Monocytes are large white blood cells formed in the bone marrow and spleen, and their numbers are reduced in AIDS patients.

Kaposi’s Sarcoma (KS)
Kaposi’s sarcoma (KS) is a skin tumor that primarily affects homosexual men with late-stage AIDS. It is characterized by reddish-purple blotches or patches on the skin or in the mouth.

African-Americans
African-Americans are mentioned in the context of Kaposi's sarcoma, where the blotches or patches may appear brownish on their skin.

Lymphoma
Lymphoma is a tumor of the lymphatic system that is the second most common form of cancer in AIDS patients. It often affects the central nervous system and develops aggressively.

ELISA
A test used to detect HIV antibodies.<SEP>ELISA (Enzyme-Linked Immunosorbent Assay) is a type of blood test used to screen blood for transfusions and diagnose patients with HIV.<SEP>Enzyme-Linked Immunosorbent Assay, a blood test used to screen for HIV antibodies. Positive results are confirmed with a Western blot or IFA assay.<SEP>Enzyme-Linked Immunosorbent Assay, a laboratory test used to detect antibodies in the blood, commonly used as a screening test for HIV.<SEP>Enzyme-Linked Immunosorbent Assay, a screening test for HIV antibodies in the blood, which may produce false-positive results and requires confirmation with other tests.<SEP>Enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay, a diagnostic blood test used to screen patients for AIDS or other viruses by detecting HIV antibodies.

Western Blot
A confirmatory blood test used to verify positive ELISA results for HIV antibodies.<SEP>A laboratory technique used to confirm the presence of specific proteins, often used to confirm HIV infection after a positive ELISA test.<SEP>A reference procedure used to confirm the diagnosis of AIDS, involving the detection of HIV antibodies by reacting patient serum against HIV antigens on a filter.<SEP>A technique used to confirm ELISA results by purifying HIV antigen and reacting it with the patient's serum to detect HIV antibodies.

IFA
Immunofluorescence Assay, a confirmatory blood test used to verify positive ELISA results for HIV antibodies.<SEP>Immunofluorescence Assay, a method used to confirm ELISA results by detecting HIV antibody in a patient's serum using a fluorescent chemical.

PCR
Polymerase Chain Reaction, a test used to detect viral nucleic acids in HIV patients, especially those with false-negative ELISA and Western blot results.<SEP>Polymerase Chain Reaction, a test used to evaluate AIDS patients with false-negative ELISA and Western blot tests by measuring viral nucleic acids in the blood.

Pneumocystis Pneumonia
An opportunistic infection common in AIDS patients, often requiring prophylactic treatment.

Thrush
A fungal infection common in AIDS patients, often requiring prophylactic treatment.

Didanosine (ddI)
A nucleoside analogue drug used in anti-retroviral treatment to suppress HIV replication.

Zalcitabine (ddC)
A nucleoside analogue drug used in anti-retroviral treatment to suppress HIV replication.

Stavudine (d4T)
A nucleoside analogue drug used in anti-retroviral treatment to suppress HIV replication.

Lamivudine (3TC)
A nucleoside analogue drug used in anti-retroviral treatment to suppress HIV replication.

Epoetin Alfa
A medication (erythropoietin) used to stimulate red blood cell production, often given to anemic patients.

Filgrastim
A medication used to increase white blood cell counts.

Sargramostim
A medication used to increase white blood cell counts.

Western Herbal Medicine
A medicine practice using herbs to enhance the immune system.<SEP>The use of herbs for medicinal purposes in Western cultures.

An organization located in New York that provides resources and support related to AIDS.

National AIDS
A national organization focused on AIDS-related issues.

A U.S. agency that provides guidelines and resources related to HIV infection.

Early HIV Infection Guideline Panel
A panel that provides guidelines for the evaluation and management of early HIV infection.

Lungs Inflammation
Inflammation of the lungs, a condition that can affect individuals with AIDS.

AIDS-Related Brain Disorders
Brain disorders that are associated with AIDS.

Anemic Patients
Patients suffering from anemia, a condition characterized by a deficiency of red blood cells.

Low White Blood Cell Counts
A condition where a patient has a reduced number of white blood cells.

Medical interventions and therapies aimed at managing and treating AIDS.

Malignancies
Cancers that can develop in individuals with AIDS.

Pregnant Women with HIV
Pregnant women who are infected with HIV.

Medical treatment using drugs to suppress HIV replication.

Infant
A baby who can contract HIV from their mother.

Alternative Treatments for AIDS
Non-traditional therapies used to manage AIDS symptoms and improve well-being.

Pain Control
Methods and therapies used to alleviate pain.

Macrobiotic Diets
A dietary approach emphasizing whole grains, vegetables, and traditional food preparation methods.

Special Diets
Specific dietary plans designed to address particular health needs.

Gay Men’s Health Crisis,Inc.
Gay Men’s Health Crisis, Inc. is an organization located in New York that provides resources and support related to AIDS.

National AIDS Hot Line
The National AIDS Hot Line provides information and support regarding AIDS in English and Spanish, including services for the hearing-impaired.

FDA
The FDA (Food and Drug Administration) approves drugs for HIV infection and AIDS-related conditions.<SEP>U.S. Food and Drug Administration, the agency that approved the first HIV home testing kit.

HIV/AIDS Treatment Information Service
HIV/AIDS Treatment Information Service provides information about treatments for HIV and AIDS via its website.

AIDS Tests
AIDS Tests are procedures used in the diagnosis and treatment of HIV patients.<SEP>AIDS tests are procedures used in the diagnosis and treatment of HIV patients.

June 1999
June 1999 is the date mentioned in the context of a publication or event related to AIDS prevention.

Individuals
Individuals are the target audience for instructions on safe sex practices to prevent the spread of AIDS.

Condoms
Condoms are a method of safe sex recommended to prevent HIV infection, other sexually transmitted diseases, and unwanted pregnancies.

SIDA
SIDA is the Spanish term for AIDS, indicating the global reach of the disease and the need for information in multiple languages.

Blood and Blood Products
Blood and blood products are carefully monitored to prevent HIV transmission, but individuals undergoing major surgery may choose to donate blood ahead of time.

Major Surgery
Major surgery is a medical procedure where individuals may consider donating blood ahead of time to prevent infection from blood transfusions.

AIDS Serology
AIDS serology refers to AIDS tests.<SEP>The analysis of blood serum to detect antibodies related to AIDS, particularly in children born to HIV-infected mothers.

Healthcare Professionals
Healthcare professionals should always wear latex gloves and avoid needle pricks when drawing blood for AIDS tests.

Latex Gloves
Latex gloves are protective equipment used by healthcare professionals to prevent infection during blood draws for AIDS tests.

Habitual Intravenous Drug User
Habitual intravenous drug users may have collapsed veins, making it difficult to draw blood for AIDS tests.

Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome
Acquired immunodeficiency syndrome is the full name of AIDS.

Home Access
The name of the only HIV home testing kit approved by the FDA as of 2001.

CD4 Cells
Cells that are targeted by the AIDS virus, disrupting their functioning and impairing the production of interleukin-2.

Lymphocytes
Lymphocytes are a type of white blood cell important in the formation of immunity.<SEP>White blood cells that are killed by HIV, further weakening the immune system.

Interleukin-2 (IL-2)
A substance produced by CD4 cells that stimulates other cells (T cells and B cells) in the human immune system to respond to infections. Its absence impairs immune response.

Blood Transfusions
A procedure that, in rare cases, can transmit HIV infection, particularly from antibody-negative asymptomatic carriers.

DNA
Deoxyribonucleic acid, the genetic material that is amplified in PCR testing to detect HIV.<SEP>Deoxyribonucleic acid, the genetic material that is amplified in the PCR test to detect HIV.

Antibody-Negative Asymptomatic Carriers
Individuals who are infected with HIV but do not show symptoms and have no detectable antibodies in their blood serum.

Antibody-Positive Asymptomatic Carriers
Individuals infected with HIV who do not show symptoms but have detectable antibodies in their blood serum.

Complete Blood Count (CBC)
A blood test used to measure the number and proportion of different types of cells in a patient's blood.

U.S.
United States of America, the country where the FDA approved the HIV home testing kit.

Laboratory
A facility that analyzes blood specimens for HIV testing.

PCR Testing
Polymerase Chain Reaction testing, a method based on the genetic sequences in HIV, used to detect the virus, but can yield false negatives due to new variants.<SEP>Polymerase Chain Reaction, a molecular test used to detect the genetic material of HIV, useful for diagnosing infants and monitoring viral load.

Corbis Corporation
A company based in New York that owns the rights to the image of the HIV virus model.

North America
A continent where HIV-1 causes most cases of AIDS.

South America
A continent where HIV-1 causes most cases of AIDS.

Antibody Response
The body's immune reaction to the HIV virus, detectable through tests like ELISA.

Virus
A microscopic infectious agent that replicates inside the living cells of an organism. In this context, referring to HIV.

Patient's Blood
Blood sample taken from a patient to monitor disease progression and treatment effectiveness.

ELISA Screening
Enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay used to detect HIV antibodies in a patient's blood, typically within one to three months of infection.

New Variants
Mutated forms of the HIV virus that can cause false negatives in PCR testing.

Antibody
A protein in the blood that identifies and helps remove disease organisms or their toxins, secreted by B cells.

AIDS Diagnostic Tests
Tests that demonstrate the presence of HIV antibody in the patient’s blood.

WBC
WBC stands for white blood cell count, an indicator of immune system health.

CBC
CBC refers to Complete Blood Count, a comprehensive blood test that includes WBC count, hematocrit, and platelet count.

Neutrophils
Neutrophils are a type of white blood cell.

Macrophage
A large white blood cell that ingests disease organisms to fight infections. HIV can infect and kill macrophages.

Monocyte
A large white blood cell formed in the bone marrow and spleen, constituting about 4% of white blood cells in normal adults.

Opportunistic Infection
An infection that develops when the immune system is weakened, commonly seen in AIDS patients.

Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR)
A test used to evaluate false-negative results in ELISA and Western blot tests by amplifying gene sequences associated with HIV for detection.

Retrovirus
A virus containing reverse transcriptase, enabling it to replicate within host cells.

Seroconversion
The change from HIV-negative to HIV-positive status during blood testing.

WBC Differential
A white blood cell count broken down into categories by cell type, used to calculate the absolute CD4+ lymphocyte count.

United States Public Health Service
A government organization that provides recommendations for serum testing frequency based on CD4+ levels in patients.

HIV Viral Load Tests
Blood tests used to monitor AIDS patients by measuring the speed of HIV replication, supplementing CD4+ counts.

Beta-Microglobulin
A protein found on the surface of human cells, elevated levels of which can indicate disease progression in AIDS patients.<SEP>A protein whose levels can be measured in the blood.

HIV-Infected Mothers
Mothers who are infected with HIV and may transmit the infection to their children during pregnancy or birth.

Thymus Gland
The gland where T cells originate.

Bone Marrow
The location where monocytes are formed.

CD4+ Count
The measurement of CD4+ lymphocyte levels in the blood, used to assess immune function in AIDS patients.

Hematocrit
The percentage of red blood cells in blood, which can be low in certain conditions.

Public Health Experts
Professionals and organizations focused on improving and protecting community health, recommending testing and monitoring of children born to mothers with HIV.

Doctors
Medical professionals who diagnose, treat, and manage illnesses and diseases, including HIV/AIDS.

P24 Antigen Capture Assay
A test that measures the p24 protein, a component of the HIV virus, used to detect HIV infection, especially before seroconversion.

Genotypic Drug Resistance Test
A test that identifies specific genetic mutations in HIV that cause resistance to certain drugs, helping to guide treatment decisions.

3TC (Lamivudine)
An antiviral drug used in HIV treatment, also known as Epivir, which may be ineffective against HIV strains with certain mutations.

Phenotypic Drug Resistance Testing
A test that directly measures the sensitivity of HIV to particular drugs, providing a more direct assessment of drug resistance than genotypic testing.

Mothers
HIV-infected women who can transmit the virus to their children during pregnancy or childbirth.

Pediatrician
A medical doctor specializing in the care of infants, children, and adolescents, who uses various techniques to diagnose HIV in children.

HIV Counselor
A trained professional who provides counseling, information, and support to individuals affected by HIV/AIDS.

Viral Load
The quantity of HIV virus present in the blood, used to monitor the progression of the infection and the effectiveness of treatment.

Serious Diseases
A range of severe health conditions, also associated with elevated beta-microglobulin levels.

Viral Core
The central part of the HIV virus, containing the p24 protein.

SDIA
Potentially an organization involved in the production or distribution of the encyclopedia.

Hematocrit Levels
A measurement of the proportion of blood volume that is composed of red blood cells, with different normal ranges for men and women.
